{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504489","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504489"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:16:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:16:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2334"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2334","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2334"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.02,0.11,0.1,0.75]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2334"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"31547"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2334","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2334"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2334"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17336"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4626"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1184"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1193"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3689"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"31547","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/31547"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman is brought by her husband to see her general practitioner due to sudden weakness of her right arm and facial drooping. Several hours earlier, she suddenly experienced difficulty verbalising yet appears to understand what her husband is saying. The husband is concerned that his wife has had a stroke. She is left-handed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUpon testing her reception of speech, she can understand and follow instructions well. However, her speech is slow and dysarthric, with significantly impaired grammar and reduced speech output. Neurological examination revealed pronounced weakness of her right arm, with facial droop that spares the forehead, with no other abnormalities found.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer vital signs were recorded at the visit:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBP 110/80 mmHg\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHR 100/min, irregular\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERR 16/min\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETemperature 36.8 \u2103\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EO2 Saturation 99% on RA\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe has no history of ischaemic heart disease or cerebrovascular disease and does not take any medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn urgent CT perfusion scan is ordered.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Assuming she has had a stroke based on the above findings, which of the following arteries is most likely to be involved?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Vertebrobasilar artery","Right anterior cerebral artery","Left anterior cerebral artery","Right middle cerebral artery","Left middle cerebral artery"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis question challenges the student\u2019s ability to correlate clinical findings of stroke with neuroanatomical location of the infarct. It is possibly secondary to new onset of atrial fibrillation given the irregular pulse, but further investigations such as an ECG will be required to work this patient up.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical picture presented by this patient suggests a cerebrovascular event. Her right-sided upper limb and facial hemiparesis suggests left brain involvement, given that the left hemisphere controls right-sided movement, and vice versa. The expressive aphasia suggest involvement of the dominant hemisphere of the brain, which is responsible for speech and language. This question tests the student\u0027s knowledge that most individuals, irrespective of handedness, are left brain dominant: for right-handed individuals, 95-99% are \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft\u003C/strong\u003E brain dominant, and even in left-handed individuals, this figure is as high as 70%. The \u003Cstrong\u003Emiddle cerebral artery\u003C/strong\u003E will be affected, as this artery supplies the language areas of the brain, as well as the motor cortex. Specifically, the superior division of the middle cerebral artery has been affected, given there is an expressive aphasia affecting Broca\u0027s area; the inferior division of the middle cerebral artery supplies Wernicke\u0027s areas, which results in a receptive aphasia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EForehead sparing of weakness suggests an upper motor neuron lesion like a stroke, as opposed to lower motor neuron lesion like Bell\u0027s palsy due to the bilateral cortical innervation of the frontalis muscle.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Right sided paresis and speech impediment is indicative of left middle cerebral artery occlusion."],"references":["Kothari R, Hall K, Brott T, Broderick J. Early stroke recognition: developing an out-of-hospital NIH Stroke Scale. Acad Emerg Med 1997; 4:986.","Corballis, MC 2014, \u2018Left Brain, Right Brain: Facts and Fantasies\u2019, PLoS Biology, vol. 12, no. 1, p. e1001767.","Mullen, M \u0026 Loomis, C 2014, Differentiating Facial Weakness Caused by Bell\u2019s Palsy vs. Acute Stroke, Journal of Emergency Medical Services, viewed 2 October 2021, \u003Chttps://www.jems.com/patient-care/differentiating-facial-weakness-caused-b/\u003E."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17336"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2334"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17336","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/17336"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-01-12T18:45:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2023-01-12T18:45:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2334"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"31547"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4626","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4626"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Ischaemic stroke","synonyms":["Acute ischemic stroke","Acute ischaemic stroke"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-10T1